snippet.textDisplay:
I've not seen data on whether nor not electric cars catch fire more often than gasoline.

However, there are several important reasons to take EV fires more seriously.

1. They can't be put out. Or more specifically, they will re-ignite themselves once oxygen is re-introduced. So you have to let them burn until they run out of fuel. This can take up to 24h+ and releases toxic smoke in the meanwhile. 

2. EVs tend to catch fire in different places than gasoline cars. One of the most common places for an EV to catch fire, is a parking garage with a charging section. Which makes it much harder for firemen to get their equipment near enough to deal with it. And traps the smoke in with anyone unlucky enough to be in the garage. The burning wrecks must be towed out of the garage, and thanks to their high weight, that's not easy. Whilst gasoline fires tend to occur after a crash in traffic. Where it's ways to get fire equipment to them.
